        <briefdescription>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>Allow constructing from <computeroutput>int</computeroutput> and other integral types. This constructor is written like this instead of a plain <computeroutput>Id(int)</computeroutput>, because we also wish to disable construction from other unrelated <computeroutput><ref refid="classMR_1_1Id" kindref="compound">Id</ref>&lt;U&gt;</computeroutput> specializations, which themselves have implicit conversions to <computeroutput>int</computeroutput>. We could also achieve that using <computeroutput>template &lt;typename U&gt; <ref refid="classMR_1_1Id" kindref="compound">Id</ref>(<ref refid="classMR_1_1Id" kindref="compound">Id</ref>&lt;U&gt;) = delete;</computeroutput>, but it turns out that that causes issues for the <computeroutput>EdgeId::operator UndirectedEdgeId</computeroutput> below. There, while <computeroutput>UndirectedEdgeId x = EdgeId{};</computeroutput> compiles with this approach, but <computeroutput>UndirectedEdgeId x(EdgeId{});</computeroutput> doesn&apos;t. So to allow both forms, this constructor must be written this way, as a template. The <computeroutput>= int</computeroutput> is there only to make the bindings emit this constructor, I don&apos;t think it affects anything else. </para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
